Content: Select the sentence from Passage 1 that supports the idea that the children are imaginative.

A.Choice: “'Father says it was once, 'Anthea said; 'he says there are shells there thousands of years old.'” (paragraph 2)

B.Choice: “Of course they had been to the edge of the gravel-pit and looked over, but they had not gone down into it for fear father should say they mustn't play there, and it was the same with the chalk-quarry.” (paragraph 3)

C.Choice: “The children dug and they dug and they dug, and their hands got sandy and hot and red, and their faces got damp and shiny.” (paragraph 8)

D.Choice: “'Fancy it having been wet sea here once, all sloppy and shiny,' said Jane, 'with fishes and conger-eels and coral and mermaids.'” (paragraph 12)

Key.Rationale: In this quotation, Jane not only imagines what the place was like ages ago, she also imagines it with a mythical mermaid.

Content: Select THREE details that should be included in a summary of Passage 1.

A.Choice: A group of children go to a gravel pit to play.

Key.Rationale: This should be included in a summary, as it is the precipitating action.

B.Choice: Each of the children has his or her own shovel.

C.Choice: Grass and wildflowers grow around the gravel pit.

D.Choice: The children decide to dig a hole through the earth.

Key.Rationale: This comprises most of the action of the story and so should be included in a summary.

E.Choice: The children's father tells them the sea is a blanket.

F.Choice: The baby is called the Lamb because of his first word.

G.Choice: The children talk about what will happen if the hold reaches Australia.

Key.Rationale: This debate and what to do about it takes up a significant amount of the passage and influences the characters' actions later on.

Content: Select choices to show how different characters advance the plot of Passage 1. More than one choice may be filled in for each character.

Key.Rationale: Anthea knows that Australia is not actually close to their hole.
Although Anthea knows that she cannot actually reach Australia, she likes to finish what she's started, so she continues to dig.

B:Jane:1.Choice: 1:feels nervous about the hole to Australia

Key.Rationale: Jane worries that the hole will cave in on them and sand will get in their eyes.

C:Robert:1.Choice: 1:feels nervous about the hole to Australia

Key.Rationale: Robert has the same worry as Jane.

Content: What is the effect of the personification in paragraph 16?

A.Choice: It shows that the gravel pit is very large.

B.Choice: It explains why the children chose to dig in the gravel pit.

C.Choice: It explains why the children's father wants them to avoid the gravel pit.

D.Choice: It gives a picture of what caused the sea to disappear form the gravel pit.

Key.Rationale: The author uses personification to describe the physical process of the geography of the area changing over time so that the sea receded.

Content: How does the description of the setting in paragraph 5 affect the overall meaning of Passage 1?

A.Choice: Describing the gravel pit as “like a giant's washbowl” creates a sense of adventure.

Key.Rationale: The passage focuses on the children's use of creativity and imagination to create a kind of alternate world to play in, and this description of the setting enhances that.

B.Choice: Mentioning the shape of the gravel pit explains that there used to be a beach there.

C.Choice: Using words like “large and wide” to describe the gravel pit shows that the children must be careful.

D.Choice: Giving the location of the gravel pit helps the reader understand how far the children walk to get there.

Content: Select TWO lines from Passage 2 that develop the speaker's desire for adventure.

A.Choice: “Three of us afloat in the meadow by the swing,” (line 1)

B.Choice: “Winds are in the air, they are blowing in the spring,” (line 3)

C.Choice: “And waves are on the meadow like the waves there are at sea.” (line 4)

D.Choice: “Shall it be to Africa, a-steering of the boat,” (line 7)

Key.Rationale: With this line, the speaker begins to address the question of how or where to seek adventure within the game that the friends are playing.

E.Choice: “Quick, and we'll escape them, they're as mad as they can be,” (line 11)

Key.Rationale: With this line, the speaker shows how the game the friends are playing results in a sense of adventure.

Content: :ibox:This problem has TWO parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
Which sentence states a theme that is shared by both Passage 1 and Passage 2?

A.Choice: Creativity helps children learn.

B.Choice: Safety is more important than having fun.

C.Choice: Imagination makes everyday life more exciting.

Key.Rationale: Both passages focus on using one's imagination to make life more adventurous.

D.Choice: It is important to work at a task until it is complete.

Content: Select TWO quotations that support the answer in Part A.

A.Choice: “The gravel-pit is not really dangerous if you don't try to climb down the edges, but go the slow safe way round by the road, as if you were a cart.” (Passage 1, paragraph 3)

B.Choice: “Cyril wanted to dig out a cave to play smugglers in, but the others thought it might bury them alive, so it ended in all spades going to work to dig a hole through the castle to Australia.” (Passage 1, paragraph 7)

Key.Rationale: This sentence from Passage 1 shows the main characters using their imaginations to make playtime more exciting.

C.Choice: “Cyril and Anthea knew that Australia was not quite so near as all that, but they agreed to stop using the spades and to go on with their hands.” (Passage 1, paragraph 11)

D.Choice: “Three of us afloat in the meadow by the swing,” (Passage 2, line 1)

E.Choice: “Winds are in the air, they are blowing in the spring,” (Passage 2, line 3)

F.Choice: “Where shall we adventure, to-day that we're afloat,” (Passage 2, line 5)

Key.Rationale: This line from Passage 2 shows the speaker using imagination to make everyday life more exciting.

Content: Read this sentence from the passage.
:box:“After 20 years of growing side-by-side with their Earth-bound equivalent as controls, no one could tell the difference.” (paragraph 8)
What does the word “equivalent” suggest about the two groups of trees?

A.Choice: They were mixed together.

B.Choice: They had similar characteristics.

Key.Rationale: The “Moon Trees” grew next to the same type of trees; however, the Earth-bound trees had not been to space. The word “equivalent” suggests the trees are similar in all other ways.

C.Choice: They were both experimented on.

D.Choice: They came from the same collection of seeds.

Content: Fill in the bubble before one sentence that supports the inference that Stuart Roosa had a positive experience with the U.S. Forest Service.

:box:	 :MC-A: It all began after Roosa was selected to pilot the Apollo 14 command module. :MC-B: As a former smoke jumper with the U.S. Forest Service, he was contacted by then chief of the Forest Service, Ed Cliff, and asked if he would be willing to take tree seeds into space.
	 :MC-C: As his way of paying tribute to the Forest Service, Roosa agreed and packed hundreds of seeds from redwood, loblolly pine, sycamore, Douglas fir and sweet gum trees into his personal travel kit. :MC-D: Roosa and his seeds orbited the moon 34 times while stationed in the command module “Kitty Hawk.”

Key.Rationale: Roosa's desire to pay tribute suggests that he had a positive experience with the U.S. Forest Service.

Content: :ibox:This problem has TWO parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
How does the passage introduce the importance of the “Moon Trees”?

A.Choice: by discussing the challenges faced by the scientists after returning

B.Choice: by listing the types of seeds that were chosen for this experiment

C.Choice: by presenting how rare experiments in space were at the time.

Key.Rationale: The passage illustrates the importance of the “Moon Trees” by describing how unusual space experiments were and by showing how people in the US and around the world responded to their introduction.

D.Choice: by describing the process of getting the seeds into space

Content: Which paragraph from the passage supports the answer to Part A?

A.Choice: paragraph 4

B.Choice: paragraph 5

Key.Rationale: This paragraph mentions how rare experiments in space were at the time and supports the answer in Part A.

C.Choice: paragraph 6

D.Choice: paragraph 7

Content: :ibox:This problem has TWO parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
What is the author's purpose for writing the passage?

A.Choice: to argue that scientists should make more journeys into space

B.Choice: to explain that the effect of seed contamination is still uncertain

C.Choice: to describe an interesting experiment involving seeds in space

Key.Rationale: The author opens the passage by declaring that all things related to the moon are mysterious, and then goes on to describe one interesting experiment which led to the Moon Trees.

D.Choice: to share information about why people should protect Moon Trees

Content: Which detail from the passage supports the purpose in Part A?

A.Choice: “It all began after Roosa was selected to pilot the Apollo 14 command module.” (paragraph 3)

B.Choice: “Scientists were curious to know if the seeds, after their journey into the microgravity of space, would sprout and look the same as Earth- grown trees.” (paragraph 5)

Key.Rationale: This explains why the experiment was interesting and what scientists hoped to learn from it.

C.Choice: “Unfortunately, after returning to Earth the seed canister burst open during the decontamination process and all the different species of seeds, not only were mixed together, but thought to be no longer useful and able to germinate.” (paragraph 6)

D.Choice: “A moon sycamore graces Roosa's grave at Arlington National Cemetery in Virginia.” (paragraph 13)

Content: Read this sentence from the passage.
:box:“Are there actually trees on the moon?” (paragraph 2)
How does this sentence help develop the author's explanation of “Moon Trees”?

A.Choice: It introduces the definition of the trees.

Key.Rationale: This rhetorical question leads into the author's definition of “Moon Trees” in the following sentence.

B.Choice: It shows where the trees originally grew.

C.Choice: It describes the experiments that were done with trees.

D.Choice: It gives an example of trees that were included in experiments.

Content: Which TWO sentences from the passage support the claim that “Moon Trees” are part of what makes the moon mysterious?

A.Choice: “Roosa and his seeds orbited the moon 34 times while stationed in the command module 'Kitty Hawk.'” (paragraph 4)

B.Choice: “Scientists were curious to know if the seeds, after their journey into the microgravity of space, would sprout and look the same as Earth-grown trees.” (paragraph 5)

Key.Rationale: This choice is correct because it addresses things that scientists did not know about the moon that their experiments with “Moon Trees” answered.

C.Choice: “In the early 70s there were very few experiments done in space.” (paragraph 5)

Key.Rationale: This choice is correct because it helps explain why so much about the moon was seen as an “unfolding mystery.”

D.Choice: “After being shipped to the Forest Service labs, it was found that most of the seeds did survive and ultimately were planted.” (paragraph 7)

E.Choice: “Many were planted as part of the nation's bicentennial celebration in 1976 and grow at national landmarks, such as the White House, Independence Square in Philadelphia, state capitols and university campuses.” (paragraph 9)

Content: Which idea from the passage does the graphic emphasize?

A.Choice: how Moon Trees grew best in warm places

B.Choice: how popular the Moon Trees became with Americans

C.Choice: how Moon Trees were only planted in the United States

D.Choice: how many different places the Moon Trees were planted

Key.Rationale: The image shows that the Moon Trees currently grow throughout the United States.

Content: Select THREE details that should be included in a summary of the passage.

A.Choice: The seeds were shipped to labs at the U.S. Forest Service.

B.Choice: Stuart Roosa was a smoke jumper for the U.S. Forest Service.

C.Choice: “Moon Trees” were planted all over the United States and the world.

Key.Rationale: This describes the legacy of the Moon Trees and should be included in a summary.

D.Choice: The vehicle that the seeds orbited the moon in was called “Kitty Hawk.”

E.Choice: NASA astronaut Stuart Roosa took a collection of tree seeds around the moon.

Key.Rationale: The story of the seeds' journey is the centerpiece of the passage.

F.Choice: Scientists wanted to see how the seeds might be affected by the gravity in space.

Key.Rationale: This detail provides the crucial rationale for why the seeds traveled into space in the first place.

G.Choice: There was a “Moon Tree” planting ceremony at NASA's Kennedy Space Center in Florida.

Content: Choose the correct word or phrase to replace the underlined part of the following sentence.
:box:Some m͟i͟g͟r͟a͟t͟o͟r͟y birds, like the painted bunting, travel as little as a few hundred miles per year.

A.Choice: migretory

B.Choice: migritory

C.Choice: migrotory

D.Choice: correct as is

Key.Rationale: The word is spelled correctly in the paragraph, so it does not need a change.

Content: Choose the correct word or phrase to replace the underlined part of the following sentence.
:box:Most do not return north until the spring or summer, when i͟t͟ ͟i͟s much more abundant.

A.Choice: food is

Key.Rationale: This answer removes the ambiguous pronoun, making clear that it is food that will become more plentiful.

B.Choice: winter is

C.Choice: that is

D.Choice: correct as is

Content: Choose the correct words or phrases to replace the underlined parts of the following sentences.

:box:The red knot spends spring and summer in northern C͟a͟n͟a͟d͟a͟ ͟w͟h͟e͟r͟e͟ ͟i͟t͟s͟ ͟b͟r͟e͟e͟d͟i͟n͟g͟ ͟g͟r͟o͟u͟n͟d͟s͟ ͟a͟r͟e͟ ͟l͟o͟c͟a͟t͟e͟d and winters as far south as the southern tip of South America.

A.Choice: Canada, where its breeding grounds are located

B.Choice: Canada where its breeding grounds are located,

C.Choice: Canada, where its breeding grounds are located,

Key.Rationale: Commas are needed on either side of the additional information.

D.Choice: correct as is

Content: :box:The w͟o͟o͟d͟ ͟t͟h͟r͟u͟s͟h͟ ͟a͟ ͟t͟y͟p͟e͟ ͟o͟f͟ ͟s͟o͟n͟g͟b͟i͟r͟d͟, travels from Central America to the Mid-Atlantic States, such as Maryland and Virginia.

A.Choice: wood thrush, a type of songbird

B.Choice: wood thrush, a type of songbird,

Key.Rationale: Commas are needed on either side of the additional information.

C.Choice: wood thrush a types of songbird

D.Choice: correct as is

Content: Choose the sentence that uses pronouns correctly to replace the underlined part of the first paragraph.

A.Choice: While theater doesn't fascinate everyone, many people love it.

Key.Rationale: “It” refers to theater, and is therefore the correct pronoun to use at the end of this sentence.

B.Choice: While theater doesn't fascinate everyone, many people love these.

C.Choice: While theater doesn't fascinate everyone, many people love those.

D.Choice: correct as is

Content: Choose the correct spelling to replace the first underlined part of the second paragraph.

A.Choice: indevidual

B.Choice: individual

Key.Rationale: This is the correct spelling of the word.

C.Choice: individule

D.Choice: correct as is

Content: Choose the correct way to complete the sentence to replace the second underlined part of the second paragraph.

A.Choice: mistakes because they will have to think on their feet to fix them.

B.Choice: mistakes. Because they will have to think on their feet to fix them.

C.Choice: mistakes, because they will have to think on their feet to fix them.

Key.Rationale: The comma correctly punctuates the nonrestrictive information.

D.Choice: correct as is

Content: Choose the sentence that corrects the unclear pronoun to replace the underlined part of the third paragraph.

A.Choice: Both the teachers and the classes are popular, and who are experts in their field.

B.Choice: Both the teachers and the classes are popular, and both are experts in their field.

C.Choice: Both the teachers and the classes are popular, and the students are experts in their field.

D.Choice: Both the teachers and the classes are popular, and the teachers are experts in their field.

Key.Rationale: The specific nouns here help to clarify the meaning of the sentence and the paragraph, avoiding an unclear pronoun.
